::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE, message = FALSE, warning = FALSE)
```
:::



# Set up


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# should haves (from last week)
library(tidyverse)
library(here)
library(janitor)
library(ggeffects)
library(performance)
library(naniar) # or equivalent
library(flextable) # or equivalent
library(car)
library(broom)
# would be nice to have
library(corrplot)
library(AICcmodavg)
library(GGally)
```
:::


# Read in the data:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
plant <- read_csv(here("data", "knb-lter-hfr.109.18", "hf109-01-sarracenia.csv")) %>% 
  # make the column names cleaner
  clean_names() %>% 
  # selecting the columns of interest
  select(totmass, species, feedlevel, sla, chlorophyll, amass, num_lvs, num_phylls)
```
:::


# Visualize the missing data:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
gg_miss_var(plant)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](workshop-08_2023-05-24_files/figure-html/missing-data-visualization-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


# Subsetting the data by dropping NAs:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
plant_subset <- plant %>% 
  drop_na(sla, chlorophyll, amass, num_lvs, num_phylls)
```
:::


# Create a correlation plot:  

(example writing) To determine the relationships between numerical variables in our dataset, we calculated Pearsons r and visually represented correlation using a correlation plot.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# calculate Pearson's r for numerical values only
plant_cor <- plant_subset %>% 
  select(feedlevel:num_phylls) %>% 
  cor(method = "pearson")
  
# creating a correlation plot
corrplot(plant_cor,
         # change the shape of what's in the cells
         method = "ellipse",
         addCoef.col = "black"
         )
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](workshop-08_2023-05-24_files/figure-html/correlation-plot-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


# Create a plot of each varable compared against the others 


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
plant_subset %>% 
  select(species:num_phylls) %>% 
  ggpairs()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](workshop-08_2023-05-24_files/figure-html/pairs-plot-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


# Starting regression here:  

(example) To determine how species and physiological characteristics predict biomass, we fit multiple linear models.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
null <- lm(totmass ~ 1, data = plant_subset)
full <- lm(totmass ~ species + feedlevel + sla + chlorophyll + amass + num_lvs + num_phylls, data = plant_subset)
```
:::


# Diagnostics

We visually assess normality and homoskedasticity of residuals using diagnostic plots for the full model:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(full)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](workshop-08_2023-05-24_files/figure-html/full-diagnostics-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


We also tested for normality using the Shapiro-Wilk test (null hypothesis: variable of interest (i.e. the residuals) are normally distributed).  

We tested for heteroskedasticity using the Breusch-Pagan test (null hypothesis: variable of interest has constant variance).

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
check_normality(full)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
Warning: Non-normality of residuals detected (p < .001).
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
check_heteroscedasticity(full)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
Warning: Heteroscedasticity (non-constant error variance) detected (p < .001).
```
:::
:::

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
null_log <- lm(log(totmass) ~ 1, data = plant_subset)
full_log <- lm(log(totmass) ~ species + feedlevel + sla + chlorophyll + amass + num_lvs + num_phylls, data = plant_subset)

plot(full_log)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](workshop-08_2023-05-24_files/figure-html/model-logs-1.png){width=672}
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](workshop-08_2023-05-24_files/figure-html/model-logs-2.png){width=672}
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](workshop-08_2023-05-24_files/figure-html/model-logs-3.png){width=672}
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](workshop-08_2023-05-24_files/figure-html/model-logs-4.png){width=672}
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
check_normality(full_log)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
OK: residuals appear as normally distributed (p = 0.107).
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
check_heteroscedasticity(full_log)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
OK: Error variance appears to be homoscedastic (p = 0.071).
```
:::
:::


Evaluate multicollinearity:


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
car::vif(full_log)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
                 GVIF Df GVIF^(1/(2*Df))
species     42.351675  9        1.231351
feedlevel    1.621993  1        1.273575
sla          1.999989  1        1.414210
chlorophyll  1.949828  1        1.396362
amass        2.872084  1        1.694722
num_lvs      2.813855  1        1.677455
num_phylls   2.995510  1        1.730754
```
:::
:::


We evaluated multicollinearity by calculating generalized variance inflation factor and determined that...  

try some more models:  

addressing the question: what set of predictor variables best explains the response?


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
model2_log <- lm(log(totmass) ~ species, data = plant_subset)
```
:::


check assumptions for model 2:

::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
plot(model2_log)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](workshop-08_2023-05-24_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-3-1.png){width=672}
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](workshop-08_2023-05-24_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-3-2.png){width=672}
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](workshop-08_2023-05-24_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-3-3.png){width=672}
:::

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](workshop-08_2023-05-24_files/figure-html/unnamed-chunk-3-4.png){width=672}
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
check_normality(model2_log)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
OK: residuals appear as normally distributed (p = 0.374).
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
check_heteroscedasticity(model2_log)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
OK: Error variance appears to be homoscedastic (p = 0.100).
```
:::
:::


compare models using Akaike's Information criterion (AIC) values: 


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
AICc(full_log)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 133.9424
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
AICc(model2_log)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 157.5751
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
AICc(null_log)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
[1] 306.0028
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
MuMIn::AICc(full_log, model2_log, null_log)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}
```
           df     AICc
full_log   17 133.9424
model2_log 11 157.5751
null_log    2 306.0028
```
:::

```{.r .cell-code}
MuMIn::model.sel(full_log, model2_log, null_log)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

:::
:::


we compared models using AIC and chose the model with the lowest value, which was...
